  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Is it a bad idea to teach high school for two years before applying to med schools?",
  "response": "Deciding to teach high school for two years before applying to medical schools is a personal choice and can have both positive and negative impacts, depending on your circumstances and goals. Here are some points to consider:\n\n### Pros:\n1. **Experience and Skills:** Teaching can help you develop strong communication, leadership, and organizational skills, all of which are valuable in the medical profession.\n2. **Unique Application Strengths:** Having teaching experience can make your medical school application stand out. It shows dedication, willingness to serve others, and ability to handle responsibility.\n3. **Personal Growth:** Spending time in a different field can give you more life experience and help you confirm your passion for medicine.\n4. **Financial Stability:** Teaching might provide you with some financial security and stability before embarking on the rigorous and expensive journey of medical school.\n5. **Networking:** You might build valuable connections within the educational community, which could be beneficial in unexpected ways.\n\n### Cons:\n1. **Application Timing:** Taking two years off before applying means you will start medical school later. This can be a disadvantage if you are eager to enter the medical profession as soon as possible.\n2. **Academic Readiness:** You might need to refresh your knowledge or retake some prerequisites if you have been out of the academic environment.\n3. **Consistent Motivation:** Ensure that your motivation for medical school remains strong and that you do not become too comfortable in your teaching career.\n4. **Opportunity Cost:** Consider what you might be giving up professionally or academically by not immediately pursuing medical school.\n\n### Considerations:\n- **Gap Year Benefits:** Many medical schools view gap years positively, as they can help applicants become more mature, gain meaningful experiences, and confirm their commitment to medicine.\n- **Pre-Med Requirements:** Ensure you are still fulfilling all the necessary requirements for medical school (volunteering, clinical experience, MCAT preparation, etc.) during your time teaching.\n- **Long-term Goals:** Reflect on your long-term career goals and how this decision will impact these aspirations.\n\nUltimately, weighing these pros and cons can help guide your decision. It can be a valuable experience if it aligns well with your personal and professional goals, but it\u2019s important to stay committed and prepared for the transition to medical school afterward.",
